      "content": "The Treaty of Oksar, even if unratified by the UN, holds potential as a foundational document of *de facto* sovereignty at the time it was executed. Under principles of customary international law, a binding agreement between recognized parties can establish a legal claim, especially if the subsequent border shifts were unilateral acts. You are correct that this document could be crucial; it serves as direct evidence of prior, recognized territorial definition that predates the disputed changes.",
